    {
      "$type": "Models.Core.Folder, Models",
      "ShowInDocs": false,
      "Name": "USA AppleExperiments",
      "ResourceName": null,
      "Children": [
        {
          "$type": "Models.Factorial.Experiment, Models",
          "DisabledSimNames": [],
          "Name": "Prosser_Apple",
          "ResourceName": null,
          "Children": [
            {
              "$type": "Models.Memo, Models",
              "Text": "*\tBased on Ebel e al (2001) - HORTSCIENCE, VOL. 36(7)\n\n*\tTrial site: Roza irrigation district in the lower Yakima valley near Prosser, Wash. (lat. 45°N; long. 119°W and 380 m above sea level)\n\n*\tSoil: Warden fine sandy loam (coarse, silty, mixed, mesic, Xerollic Camborthids) that was uniform down the profile and overlaid fractured basalt bedrock \t\n\n*\tThe permanent wilting and field capacity were 8% (80 mm·m–1) and 28% (280 mm·m–1) by volume, respectively - total available soil water was 200 mm·m–1 for the two orchards. \n\n*\tThe shallow soil (mean depth = 0.8 m) and deeper soil (average depth = 1.2 m) had 160 and 240 mm of total water available at field capacity (FC), respectively.\n\n*\tIrrigation treatments: withholding irrigation all season or from 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, 15 or 17 weeks before harvest.\n\n*\tTotal pan evaporation was 1005 mm and precipitation was negligible from May through September.",
              "Name": "ExperimentDescription",
              "ResourceName": null,
              "Children": [],
              "Enabled": false,
              "ReadOnly": false
            },
            {
              "$type": "Models.Memo, Models",
